 romances offer valuable insights into the evolution of Arthurian romance,the history of reception of Chrétien's work, and the mentality and culture of one of the most remarkable courts to flourish in the late middle ages. This volume presents the first English prose translations of the writings,accompanied by an introduction presenting the historical, cultural, and literary context, and notes. Joan Tasker Grimbert is Professor of French at the Catholic University of America, Washington, DC; Carol J. Chase is Professor Emerita of French at Knox College, Galesburg, Illinois.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFrench prose literaturexHistory and criticismyTo 1500. 0aFrench prose literatureyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthurian romance.  aBurgundian Erec.  aChrétien de Troyes.  aCligés.  aMiddle French reworkings.  afifteenth century.  ahistorical significance.  aprose reworkings.1 aChase, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimbert, Joan Tasker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846156854423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846156854/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles